2019 State Profile - Wyoming

Child Maltreatment Victims

About this Report

This report provides data from 2019 on child maltreatment victims in Wyoming. Child abuse and neglect, also referred to as child maltreatment, encompasses any recent action or failure to act by a parent or caregiver that results in significant physical or emotional harm, sexual abuse, exploitation, or death. It also includes any behavior (or lack of action) that poses an immediate risk of serious harm to a child. For more information on child maltreatment, visit the Childrenâs Bureauâs Child Maltreatment page from the Office of the Administration for Children and Families. The data for this report was sourced from the Kids Count Data Center.


Victims of child maltreatment

In 2019, there were 133,577 children in Wyoming. During that same year, state officials reported that 1,095 children were victims of maltreatment, representing a rate of 8 per 1,000 children in the population. This report highlights the percentage of child maltreatment victims in Wyoming, broken down by the following categories:

  • Gender
  • Race and Ethnicity
  • Age
  • Maltreatment Type
